Naming hints.

- *Prefix `Is`* for properties of measures: `IsProbabilityMeasure őľ`,
  `IsFiniteMeasure őľ`, `IsSigmaFiniteMeasure őľ`.
- *Prefix `ae`* (short for "almost everywhere"): `ae őľ` is the filter
  of conull sets; `AEMeasurable f`, `AEStronglyMeasurable f`,
  `AEEqFun` are ae-variants of stronger regularity properties.
- The integral symbol `‚ąę` takes a binder `‚ąę x, ...` followed by the
  measure `‚ąāőľ`.  Without `‚ąāőľ`, the integral is with respect to the
  default `volume` measure.
- `‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě` is the preferred codomain for measures: they take values in
  `[0, ‚ąě]`.  Coercions to/from `‚ĄĚ` use `ENNReal.toReal`,
  `ENNReal.ofReal`.
- Almost-everywhere statements are just the filter quantifier `‚ąÄŠ∂†`
  applied to the `ae` filter: `‚ąÄŠĶź x ‚ąāőľ, p x` is definitionally
  `‚ąÄŠ∂† x in őľ.ae, p x`.

# Sigma-algebras: MeasurableSpace
%%%
tag := "measurable-space"
%%%

A *sigma-algebra* (or *measurable space*) on a type `őĪ` is specified by the
typeclass `MeasurableSpace őĪ`. It tells Lean which subsets of `őĪ` are
*measurable*.

{docstring MeasurableSpace}

```lean
-- ‚ĄĚ has a measurable space structure (the Borel sigma-algebra)
#check (inferInstance : MeasurableSpace ‚ĄĚ)

-- The whole space and the empty set are measurable
example : MeasurableSet (Set.univ : Set ‚ĄĚ) :=
  MeasurableSet.univ

example : MeasurableSet (‚ąÖ : Set ‚ĄĚ) :=
  MeasurableSet.empty

-- Complements of measurable sets are measurable
example (s : Set ‚ĄĚ) (hs : MeasurableSet s) : MeasurableSet sŠ∂ú :=
  hs.compl
```

Countable unions of measurable sets are measurable:

{docstring MeasurableSet.iUnion}

On `‚ĄĚ` (and other topological spaces), the default sigma-algebra is the
*Borel sigma-algebra*, generated by the open sets.

# Measurable functions
%%%
tag := "measurable-functions"
%%%

A function `f : őĪ ‚Üí ő≤` between measurable spaces is *measurable* if the
preimage of every measurable set is measurable.

{docstring Measurable}

```lean
-- The identity function is measurable
example {őĪ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace őĪ] :
    Measurable (id : őĪ ‚Üí őĪ) :=
  measurable_id

-- Composition of measurable functions is measurable
example {őĪ ő≤ ő≥ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace őĪ] [MeasurableSpace ő≤]
    [MeasurableSpace ő≥] (f : őĪ ‚Üí ő≤) (g : ő≤ ‚Üí ő≥)
    (hf : Measurable f) (hg : Measurable g) :
    Measurable (g ‚ąė f) :=
  hg.comp hf
```

Continuous functions are measurable (with Borel sigma-algebras):

{docstring Continuous.measurable}

Important: every continuous function is measurable (when both spaces carry
the Borel sigma-algebra), but not vice versa.

# Measures
%%%
tag := "measures"
%%%

A *measure* on a measurable space `őĪ` is a countably additive function from
measurable sets to `[0, ‚ąě]`. In Mathlib, measures take values in `‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě`
(the extended nonnegative reals, typed `\R\ge0\infty` or using `ENNReal`).

{docstring MeasureTheory.Measure}

```lean
-- A measure assigns a value in ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě to each measurable set
example {őĪ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace őĪ]
    (őľ : MeasureTheory.Measure őĪ) (s : Set őĪ) : ENNReal :=
  őľ s

-- The measure of the empty set is 0
example {őĪ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace őĪ]
    (őľ : MeasureTheory.Measure őĪ) : őľ ‚ąÖ = 0 :=
  MeasureTheory.measure_empty
```

Monotonicity: if `s ‚äÜ t`, then `őľ s ‚Č§ őľ t`:

{docstring MeasureTheory.measure_mono}

# The Lebesgue measure on ‚ĄĚ
%%%
tag := "lebesgue-measure"
%%%

The standard measure on `‚ĄĚ` is the *Lebesgue measure*, available as
`MeasureTheory.volume` (or via the notation `volume`).

The Lebesgue measure of an interval:

{docstring Real.volume_Icc}

```lean
-- volume is a measure on ‚ĄĚ
open MeasureTheory in
#check (volume : Measure ‚ĄĚ)
```

# A small worked computation
%%%
tag := "lebesgue-worked"
%%%

A concrete sanity check: the Lebesgue measure of the closed unit
interval is `1`.

```lean
open MeasureTheory in
example : volume (Set.Icc (0 : ‚ĄĚ) 1) = 1 := by
  rw [Real.volume_Icc]
  simp
```

Mathlib also gives the volume of `Ico`, `Ioo`, `Ioc` (all equal to
`b - a` when `a ‚Č§ b`); a half-open interval can be written as a
disjoint union with a single point, and points have measure zero
(`Real.volume_singleton`).

# Integration
%%%
tag := "integration"
%%%

Mathlib provides the Bochner integral `‚ąę x, f x ‚ąāőľ` (typed `\int`), which
generalizes both the Lebesgue integral for real-valued functions and the
integral for Banach-space-valued functions.

{docstring MeasureTheory.integral}

Linearity of the integral:

{docstring MeasureTheory.integral_add}

{docstring MeasureTheory.integral_smul}

Integral over an indicator function:

{docstring MeasureTheory.integral_indicator}

For nonnegative functions, there is also the `‚ąę‚ĀĽ` (lower Lebesgue integral)
taking values in `‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě`:

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.lintegral
-- ‚ąę‚ĀĽ x, f x ‚ąāőľ : ‚ĄĚ‚Č•0‚ąě
```

# Convergence theorems
%%%
tag := "convergence-theorems"
%%%

The fundamental convergence theorems of measure theory are available in Mathlib:

*Monotone Convergence Theorem*: If `f‚āÄ ‚Č§ f‚āĀ ‚Č§ f‚āā ‚Č§ ...` is an increasing
sequence of nonnegative measurable functions, then
`‚ąę‚ĀĽ x, (‚®Ü n, f n x) ‚ąāőľ = ‚®Ü n, ‚ąę‚ĀĽ x, f n x ‚ąāőľ`.

{docstring MeasureTheory.lintegral_iSup}

*Dominated Convergence Theorem*: If `f‚āô ‚Üí f` pointwise a.e., and
`|f‚āô| ‚Č§ g` a.e. for an integrable `g`, then `‚ąę x, f‚āô x ‚ąāőľ ‚Üí ‚ąę x, f x ‚ąāőľ`.

{docstring MeasureTheory.tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence}

These theorems are stated using filters: convergence of the integrals is
expressed as `Filter.Tendsto` with respect to `Filter.atTop`.

# Probability measures
%%%
tag := "probability-measures"
%%%

A measure `őľ` is a *probability measure* if `őľ Set.univ = 1`. Mathlib uses
the typeclass `MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure őľ` for this.

{docstring MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure}

```lean
-- If őľ is a probability measure, then őľ(s) ‚Č§ 1 for all s
example {őĪ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace őĪ]
    (őľ : MeasureTheory.Measure őĪ)
    [MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure őľ] (s : Set őĪ) :
    őľ s ‚Č§ 1 := by
  calc őľ s ‚Č§ őľ Set.univ :=
        MeasureTheory.measure_mono (Set.subset_univ s)
    _ = 1 :=
        MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure.measure_univ
```

There is also `MeasureTheory.IsFiniteMeasure őľ` for finite measures and
`MeasureTheory.SigmaFinite őľ` for sigma-finite measures.

# Almost everywhere and ae-filter
%%%
tag := "ae-filter"
%%%

Many statements in measure theory hold "almost everywhere" (a.e.), meaning
outside a set of measure zero. In Mathlib, this is captured by the
*ae-filter* `MeasureTheory.Measure.ae őľ`, which is the filter of sets whose
complement has measure zero.

{docstring MeasureTheory.ae}

```lean
-- "f = g almost everywhere" means {x | f x ‚Č† g x} has measure zero
open MeasureTheory in
example {őĪ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace őĪ]
    (őľ : Measure őĪ) (f g : őĪ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ) :
    f =ŠĶź[őľ] g ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄŠ∂† x in ae őľ, f x = g x :=
  Iff.rfl
```

This is a beautiful example of the filter framework in action: "almost
everywhere" is just "eventually" with respect to the ae-filter.

# Conditional expectation
%%%
tag := "conditional-expectation"
%%%

For probability theory, Mathlib provides conditional expectation with respect
to a sub-sigma-algebra. This is an advanced topic, but the key definition is:

{docstring MeasureTheory.condExp}

The conditional expectation `őľ[f | m]` (notation
`MeasureTheory.condExp m őľ f`) is the unique (up to
`őľ`-almost-everywhere equality) function `g : őĪ ‚Üí E` such that

- `g` is `m`-measurable, where `m` is a sub-sigma-algebra of the
  ambient sigma-algebra on `őĪ`;
- for every `m`-measurable set `s`,
  `‚ąę x in s, f x ‚ąāőľ = ‚ąę x in s, g x ‚ąāőľ`.

In probability terms: `őľ[f | m]` is the best `m`-measurable
predictor of `f` in the `L¬≤` sense.  The defining property is
captured by `MeasureTheory.setIntegral_condExp`.  Mathlib has the
linearity, monotonicity, tower, and Jensen properties; the API
lives in the `MeasureTheory` namespace and uses `condExp_` as a
prefix.

The conditional expectation `őľ[f | m]` is the unique (a.e.) `m`-measurable
function that agrees with `f` in integral over every `m`-measurable set.

# Summary of key Mathlib API for measure theory
%%%
tag := "measure-api-summary"
%%%

:::table +header
* + Concept
  + Mathlib name
* + Sigma-algebra
  + `MeasurableSpace őĪ`
* + Measurable set
  + `MeasurableSet s`
* + Measurable function
  + `Measurable f`
* + Measure
  + `MeasureTheory.Measure őĪ`
* + Lebesgue measure
  + `MeasureTheory.volume`
* + Bochner integral
  + `‚ąę x, f x ‚ąāőľ`
* + Lebesgue integral
  + `‚ąę‚ĀĽ x, f x ‚ąāőľ`
* + Probability measure
  + `IsProbabilityMeasure őľ`
* + Almost everywhere
  + `‚ąÄŠ∂† x in őľ.ae, p x`
* + Integrable
  + `MeasureTheory.Integrable f őľ`
